maybe this is better re-written like so (more idiomatic when it comes to testing style)

```
func TestGetProjectName(t *testing.T) {
	testStr := "junk test[junk] junk junk junk"
	got, err := getProjectName(testStr)
	if err != nil {
		t.Fatalf("getProjectName(%q) got an expected error: %s", testStr, err)
	}

	if want := "test"; want != got {
		t.Errorf("getProjectName(%q): want %s got %s", want, got)
	}
}
```

So basically, there's no need to continue if there was an error, also the format of the message is far more interesting if it's function(args) and return. Also I know this isn't really Go style specific but I personally prefer not to see empty line right after `{` or right before `}` feels like a wasted space on my screen :trollface:

maybe go with an *optimistic* approach since people are more and more likely to have the `1.x` version installed.

```
try:
    return self.as_dict()
except AttributeError:
    return vars(self)
```

